  "local_port": 58812,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do we forget any Wi-Fi in Windows 10?",
  "response": "To forget a Wi-Fi network in Windows 10, follow these steps:\n\n### Method 1: Using Settings\n1. **Open Settings**:\n   - Press `Win + I` to open the **Settings** app.\n\n2. **Go to Network & Internet**:\n   - Click on **Network & Internet**.\n\n3. **Select Wi-Fi**:\n   - In the left-hand menu, click on **Wi-Fi**.\n\n4. **Manage Known Networks**:\n   - Under the Wi-Fi section, click on **Manage known networks**.\n\n5. **Forget the Network**:\n   - Find the Wi-Fi network you want to forget in the list.\n   - Click on the network name, then click the **Forget** button.\n\n### Method 2: Using Command Prompt\n1. **Open Command Prompt**:\n   - Press `Win + X` and select **Command Prompt (Admin)** or **Windows PowerShell (Admin)** from the menu.\n\n2. **List All Networks**:\n   - Type the following command and press Enter:\n     ```\n     netsh wlan show profiles\n     ```\n   - This will display a list of all saved Wi-Fi networks.\n\n3. **Delete a Specific Network**:\n   - To forget a specific network, type the following command and press Enter (replace `NETWORK_NAME` with the actual name of the network):\n     ```\n     netsh wlan delete profile name=\"NETWORK_NAME\"\n     ```\n\n### Method 3: Using Control Panel (Older Method)\n1. **Open Control Panel**:\n   - Press `Win + S`, type **Control Panel**, and press Enter.\n\n2. **Network and Sharing Center**:\n   - Go to **Network and Internet** > **Network and Sharing Center**.\n\n3. **Manage Wireless Networks**:\n   - Click on **Manage wireless networks** in the left-hand menu (note: this option may not be available in all versions of Windows 10).\n\n4. **Forget the Network**:\n   - Right-click the Wi-Fi network you want to forget and select **Remove network**.\n\nAfter following these steps, the Wi-Fi network will be forgotten, and Windows 10 will no longer automatically connect to it.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
